source_id: STP1023-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_8th Volume_010_chunk1
evidence_span: Three different types of materials were used. Types I and II are Zircaloy-4 melts, totaling 38 different heats, which have been produced with variations in tin over the range of 1.12 to 1.79%, iron + chromium 0.21 to 0.36%, oxygen 0.13 to 0.20%, carbon 40 to 283 ppm, silicon 14 to 177 ppm phosphorus 3 to 22 ppm, and aluminum 25 to 82 ppm.
process_step: beta-forged, beta-quenched, hot rolled to 6 mm, air annealed at 780°C for 30-60 min, oxide removed, cold rolled with 25-35% reduction, intermediate and final anneals at 730°C for 120 min
conditions: pressurized water at 350°C (380-840 days); high pressure steam at 400°C (180-397 days)
corrosion_data: time to transition from cubic to linear rate increases and post transition rate decreases with decreasing tin and carbon and increasing silicon content

extra_properties.precipitate_characteristics: intermetallic precipitates characterized by SEM and TEM

source_id: STP1023-EB-Zirconium in the Nuclear Industry_8th Volume_010_chunk1
evidence_span: Type II material consists of nine special melts beyond the Zircaloy-4 specification. The alloy elements covered the following ranges: tin: 0.24 to 1.64%; iron: 0.05 to 0.53%; chromium: 0.04 to 1.05%; and nickel: 0.003 to 0.046%.
process_step: beta-forged, beta-quenched into 30% polyethylene glycol solution (2 K/s cooling rate), hot rolled to 3 mm at 780°C, air annealed at 780°C for 30-60 min, oxide removed, cold rolled with 25-35% reduction, intermediate and final anneals at 730°C for 120 min
conditions: pressurized water at 350°C (380-840 days); high pressure steam at 400°C (180-397 days)
corrosion_data: markedly accelerated corrosion at Fe+Cr ≤ 0.15% especially in steam; high Cr/Fe ratios resulted in high corrosion even at moderately high levels of both elements

extra_properties.precipitate_characteristics: intermetallic precipitates characterized by SEM and TEM
